		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2024"></a><br><code>sle2024/paper12</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Statically and Dynamically Delayed Sampling for Typed Probabilistic Programming Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GizemÇaylak.html">Gizem Çaylak</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielLundén.html">Daniel Lundén</a>, <a href="../profile/ViktorSenderov.html">Viktor Senderov</a>, <a href="../profile/DavidBroman.html">David Broman</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695634">10.1145/3687997.3695634</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> A central issue is reconciling delayed sampling with static typing when random variables change representation/types.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It introduces compile-time delayed-sampling optimizations that move inference work from runtime to compilation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> It also provides runtime support for dynamically delayed sampling when static optimization is insufficient.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> Both static and dynamic approaches are evaluated on realistic probabilistic models.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
